00:04:31.480 --> 00:04:35.600
If I wrote a function like this in R, and then I wanted that function to be accessible

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:40.140
to other tools, we're going to ignore Tableau for a moment and just say, look, I want some

00:04:40.140 --> 00:04:44.760
generic other service to have access to this thing that I wrote.

00:04:44.760 --> 00:04:48.519
The best and easiest way to do that in R is using the plumber package.

00:04:48.519 --> 00:04:49.959
And here's an example of what that might look like.

00:04:49.959 --> 00:04:54.440
If I bring in the plumber package, first of all I have to bring the package into my workspace,

00:04:54.440 --> 00:04:59.799
and then all I need to do is add a few special comments to my script that indicate, hey,

00:04:59.799 --> 00:05:05.040
this should be an API that's listening for requests from other services.

00:05:05.040 --> 00:05:09.679
It's very straightforward and easy to use, especially if I'm already used to using R.

00:05:09.679 --> 00:05:11.959
Now let's take that and make it a little bit more specific.

00:05:11.959 --> 00:05:15.760
Let's say that instead of just any generic service out there, I actually want this to

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:17.239
be used from within Tableau.

00:05:17.239 --> 00:05:22.079
I want Tableau to be able to submit data to this function, and I want this function to

00:05:22.079 --> 00:05:24.679
execute and return the data back to Tableau.

00:05:24.679 --> 00:05:31.119
Well, I could write my own very unique API to do that, or I could use the plumber Tableau

00:05:31.119 --> 00:05:36.880
package, which handles a lot of the specifics behind the scenes to make this API work specifically

00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:39.720
with Tableau workbooks and dashboards.

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:43.160
As you notice, again, I've highlighted the differences here between a traditional plumber

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:47.000
API and this new plumber Tableau API, and they're very minimal.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:51.000
I bring in the plumber Tableau package, I add a few additional comments that indicate

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:54.679
what type of data I'm expecting from Tableau, what type of data I'm going to be returning

00:05:54.679 --> 00:05:58.920
to Tableau, and then the most significant piece is that piece there at the bottom where

00:05:58.920 --> 00:06:04.880
I indicate that I'm creating a Tableau extension.

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:08.079
If we do the same thing on the Python side, we could bring in scikit-learn, we could define

00:06:08.079 --> 00:06:12.959
a function that creates and trains a random forest and again spits out the predicted outcomes

