based on the input data that we received.

00:06:15.720 --> 00:06:19.480
If I want to make this a generically available service, I could use a tool like fast API,

00:06:19.480 --> 00:06:23.600
I can bring in the fast API module, I can define an app and then I can define routes

00:06:23.600 --> 00:06:27.880
on that app that are functions that are listening for incoming input.

00:06:27.880 --> 00:06:31.480
Just like we saw on the R side with plumber Tableau, there's a new package called fast

00:06:31.480 --> 00:06:33.799
API Tableau that does the same thing.

00:06:33.799 --> 00:06:36.640
In fact, it's maybe even a little bit easier than what we saw on the plumber Tableau side

00:06:36.640 --> 00:06:41.760
because all I need to do is change import fast API to import fast API Tableau and I

00:06:41.760 --> 00:06:45.920
need to change my app instantiation instead of saying it's a fast API app, I now just

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:48.239
say it's a fast API Tableau app.

00:06:48.239 --> 00:06:51.920
Everything else remains the same.

00:06:51.920 --> 00:06:57.880
Now once I've developed these extensions, I might have used RStudio workbench to develop

00:06:57.880 --> 00:07:01.640
these, I might have developed these locally, but once I've developed them, I need somewhere

00:07:01.640 --> 00:07:05.399
where they can be hosted so that I can access them from within Tableau.

00:07:05.399 --> 00:07:08.679
The easiest place to do that is RStudio connect.

00:07:08.679 --> 00:07:12.480
And here's an example of what it looks like when I've published these two extensions onto

00:07:12.480 --> 00:07:14.160
RStudio connect.

