00:15:09.340 --> 00:15:10.340
It's not.

00:15:10.340 --> 00:15:13.140
I have a 6-year-old daughter who just had her first piano recital, and it was exactly

00:15:13.140 --> 00:15:14.140
what it needed to be.

00:15:14.140 --> 00:15:18.460
She didn't need to be playing the violin and the trumpet and everything all at once.

00:15:18.460 --> 00:15:20.460
The piano recital was enough.

00:15:20.460 --> 00:15:24.780
And it's up to us as the data scientists, as the analysts, to decide what level of insight

00:15:24.780 --> 00:15:28.539
is the appropriate level for the analysis that we're doing.

00:15:28.539 --> 00:15:32.260
It's important to understand that we have a whole host of tools, like JJ kind of alluded

00:15:32.260 --> 00:15:36.419
to in his talk this morning, we continue to look at this ecosystem and look for ways in

00:15:36.419 --> 00:15:41.020
which we can participate in the broad scientific computing ecosystem and that includes tools

00:15:41.020 --> 00:15:45.140
like Tableau and the integrations that we've done there.

00:15:45.140 --> 00:15:48.580
If you're interested in learning more, there's some resources here, there's a GitHub repository

00:15:48.580 --> 00:15:52.900
that has several different examples of how these different extensions can work with different

00:15:52.900 --> 00:15:56.260
Tableau workbooks and things like that, and you can learn from those examples.

00:15:56.260 --> 00:16:00.099
The slides and all the content from this talk will be made available on GitHub shortly after

00:16:00.099 --> 00:16:02.059
I've kind of finished everything up today.

00:16:02.059 --> 00:16:05.539
And finally, I just want to say thank you, it's been great being back in person, and

00:16:05.539 --> 00:16:06.539
if there's any questions, we can take those now.

00:16:06.539 --> 00:16:07.539
Thank you.

00:16:07.539 --> 00:16:08.539
Thank you.

00:16:08.539 --> 00:16:08.539


